data.text:
For our third annual edition of the Most Influential People Shaping Policy, we again sought out smart, innovative Washingtonians who care about issues and spend a lot of time thinking about them.

The selection process is not easy. Despite what the news says, there are a lot of people in Washington who care deeply about this country and advocate on behalf of changes and ideas they believe will make the nation better.

Our list is determined by several factors. We look for those who have deep subject-matter expertise and significant understanding of how the nationâ€™s capital works, with the goal of getting action. We want people who understand the nuances and complexities of a particular issue area. And we focus on policy subjects we believe are of special relevance right now to our slate of elected officials.

Weâ€™ve tried to make choices across the ideological spectrum and avoid big-name â€œhired gunsâ€ whose influence often derives more from their communication skills and network than from their expertise in a particular area. We also didnâ€™t include elected officials and Capitol Hill or administration staffersâ€”the influencees, so to speak. Some people or organizations may strike you as having a harmful effect. Weâ€™re not passing judgment on whether every personâ€™s influence is for the greater good. We want to highlight those who wield it.

Many of those selected have indeed served government in some capacity, such as Alexandra Veitch, who worked for former senator Barbara Mikulski but now helps YouTube with public policy. Or John Lettieri, a onetime GOP Hill staffer who today leads the Economic Innovation Group and pushes for better economic policies. We believe that the people weâ€™ve highlighted possess special insight into how to get an issue elevated. We also think some of the names here are likely to land in government in the future, either because of their ambition to serve or because theyâ€™ll be tapped for their expertise.

Ultimately, every one of the influencers shares a drive to understand a policy issue and propel it forward. Washington has always been a city of thinkers. Weâ€™re confident these are among the best brains in the city.

â€”Catherine Merrill

Washingtonian President and CEO
